For the start symbol we have  
S → NT5 NT8  

Thus the string generated by S must be the concatenation of a block produced by NT5 followed immediately by a block produced by NT8, and the very last token of the whole string must come from NT8.

Examine every possible production for NT8 (it has exactly three):

1. NT8 → NT15 NT11  
   The last token comes from NT11.  
   NT11 can yield only t6, t1 or t28. (never t3)

2. NT8 → NT12 NT2  
   If NT2 → 't9', the last token is t9;  
   if NT2 → NT4 NT27, the last token is t10. (never t3)

3. NT8 → NT4 NT3  
   The last token comes from NT3.  
   NT3 can end in t12, t18, t28, t11, t22, t29, t4 or t9, but there is no derivation that ends in t3.

Consequently NT8 can never generate a terminal t3 as its final symbol.

In the given string  
t18 t10 t12 t12 t9 t10 t3 t11 t8 t11 t9 t29 t23 t1 t3  
the last token is t3, so it would have to be the final symbol produced by NT8.  
Since NT8 can never end in t3, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

To be generated, the string must be derived from the start rule  

 S → NT5 NT8  

hence the whole word has to split into two contiguous substrings,
the first produced by NT5 and the second by NT8.

The given word begins with the terminal t19.  
Among all rules with left‑hand side NT5 the only possibilities that allow t19
to appear as the very first symbol of the derived string are the rules in which
the first component on the right‑hand side can yield t19 directly:

 NT5 → NT27 NT18  (NT27 ⇒ t19)  
 NT5 → NT18 NT13  (NT18 ⇒ NT27 NT21 ⇒ t19 …)

Any other NT5‑rule would force some symbol different from t19
(t21, t4, t8, …) to appear first, which is impossible.

1.  NT5 → NT27 NT18  
 After NT27 generates the first t19, NT18 must generate the remainder
     of the prefix.  
 Yet every possible expansion of NT18 starts with one of  
  t23 (NT18 → 't23'),  
  t19 (NT18 → NT27 NT21), or  
  t9 (NT18 → NT2 NT23, because NT2 ⇒ t9).  
 None of these starts with the required second symbol t18,
 so NT18 cannot yield the substring beginning with t18.
 Thus this rule cannot produce the needed prefix “t19 t18 …”.

2.  NT5 → NT18 NT13  
 For the first symbol to be t19, NT18 would have to employ the expansion
 NT18 → NT27 NT21 again (NT27 ⇒ t19).  
 But that produces at least two terminals, the second one being generated
 by NT21.  NT21 can only yield t0 (NT21 ⇒ 't0'), t19 (via NT21→NT0 NT29 etc.)
 or t28/t6 via longer derivations, never t18.  
 Therefore the second terminal produced here can never be the required t18,
 so this rule also fails to match the prefix “t19 t18”.

Consequently NT5 is unable to derive any string whose first two
symbols are t19 t18, and therefore the start symbol S
can not generate the given word at all.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start‑symbol is  

S  →  NT5 NT8  

so every sentence the grammar generates is a concatenation of a string from NT5 followed by a string from NT8.

Look at the possible ways NT8 can produce terminals (these are the only productions for NT8):

1. NT8 → NT15 NT11  
    NT15 → NT11 NT9          (the only rule for NT15)  
    NT11 → 't6' | 't1' | 't28'  
    NT9  → … , but its terminals are never 't1'

   Hence any string from this alternative has exactly 3 terminals and ends with the token produced by NT11, i.e. it ends with t6, t1 or t28, and its first two terminals are
   (t6|t1|t28)  followed by a token from NT9.

2. NT8 → NT12 NT2  
    NT12 → 't28' | 't18' | 't11' | …  
    NT2  → 't9'

   Therefore every string from this alternative ends with t9.

3. NT8 → NT4 NT3  
    NT4 → 't27'  
    NT3 → 't12'                 | NT12 NT17  
          | NT28 NT7             | NT9 NT3  
          | NT25 NT13            | NT6 NT12  
          | NT15 NT7

   In every sub‑case the last token produced by NT3 is one of  
   t12, t4, t9, t18, t22, t28, or t29 – never t1.

To summarise: every string derivable from NT8 must
• end with t9, or
• be of length 3 and match (t6|t1|t28)  · (token from NT9) · (t6|t1|t28).

Now examine the string we are asked to parse:

t21 t4 t22 t27 t1 t4 t28 t1 t21 t9 t18 t28 t6 t4 t28 t4 t28 t21 t4 t1

It ends with t1, but the suffix of length 3 is “… t21 t4 t1”, which does not fit the pattern required in the first alternative (the first token would have to be t6, t1 or t28, not t21), and the other two alternatives for NT8 cannot end with t1 at all.

Hence no suffix of this string can be generated by NT8, so S cannot generate the whole string.

Therefore the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

For S to generate the string, S → NT5 NT8 must split the 22 terminals into a prefix produced by NT5 and a suffix produced by NT8.

NT8 has exactly three binary rules  
 1) NT8 → NT15 NT11 (start token ∈ {t1,t6,t28}; final token ∈ {t1,t6,t28})  
 2) NT8 → NT12 NT2 (start token ∈ {t28,t18,t11}; second token is t9)  
 3) NT8 → NT4 NT3 (start token is t27)

Hence any string derived from NT8 must begin with one of  
 t27, t28, t18, t11, t1, t6.

Looking at the target string
 t3 t27 t10 t21 t29 t21 t11 t10 t12 t0 t1 t9 t3 t8 t22 t6 t10 t29 t18 t9 t12 t4
the only positions whose token is in that set are positions 2 (t27), 7 (t11), 11 (t1), 16 (t6) and 19 (t18).  
These give the only possible split points between NT5 and NT8.

• If NT8 starts at position 2, it must use rule 3 (t27 followed by NT3).  
  NT3 can start with t28, t18, t11, t12, t1, t6 or t27, or with what NT9 can start.  
  NT9 can start with t27, t28, t18, t11, t1, t6, t29, t21 or t4, but never with t10,  
  yet the next token in the string is t10.  Thus this split is impossible.

• If NT8 starts at position 7 (token t11), the only rule that yields t11 first is rule 2, giving the fixed two‑token prefix “t11 t9”; the actual substring is “t11 t10…”, so impossible.

• If NT8 starts at position 11 (token t1), only rule 1 applies, forcing the last token produced by NT8 to be t1, t6 or t28, but the final token of the string is t4, hence impossible.

• If NT8 starts at position 16 (token t6), again only rule 1 applies, so NT8 would have to end with t1, t6 or t28, not the required final token t4 – impossible.

• If NT8 starts at position 19 (token t18), only rule 2 applies, fixing NT8’s length at 2 and making its second token t9; the substring is “t18 t9 t12 t4”, so impossible.

All possible placements of NT8 fail. Therefore no derivation of the given string from S exists.

No

In the grammar the only non‑terminal that can produce the terminal symbol t1 is NT11:

 NT11 → 't1'

Because the given string ends in t1, that final token must come from a leaf NT11 in any derivation.

The only way for NT11 to appear as the right‑most child of the start symbol S is through the rule

 NT8 → NT15 NT11                               (1)

(the alternative rules for NT8 place NT11 nowhere, or do not contain NT11 at all).  
Consequently, in every successful derivation we must have

 S ⇒ NT5 NT8 ⇒ NT5 (NT15 NT11)

so the last token (position 23) is t1 (from NT11), and the preceding portion of the suffix (positions 1 … 22 of NT8’s yield) has to be generated by NT15.

But NT15 itself is ruled by

 NT15 → NT11 NT9                                (2)

Hence the very first token produced by NT15 (that is, token 22 of the whole string) must again come from an NT11, and can therefore only be t1, t6 or t28 (the three terminals NT11 can produce).

In the string we were given, token 22 is

 t11                                            (≠ t1, t6, t28)

which makes it impossible for token 22 to originate from that obligatory NT11.  
Therefore no derivation using rules (1) and (2) can match the tail “… t11 t1”, and there is no other way for NT11 to appear in the required right‑most position.

Hence the grammar cannot generate the supplied string.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT5 NT8  

so the first token of any generated string must come from NT5.

Examine every production that can appear at the leftmost position of an NT5‑derivation:

NT5 →  
 NT19 NT26 (first token from NT19)  
 NT18 NT13 (first token from NT18)  
 NT27 NT18 (first token from NT27)  
 NT26 NT13 (first token from NT26)  
 NT0 NT10  (first token from NT0)  
 NT21 NT12 (first token from NT21)  
 NT5 NT9  (first token from NT5 again)  
 NT13 NT27 (first token from NT13)  
 NT17 NT14 (first token from NT17)  
 NT9 NT21  (first token from NT9)  
 't8'    (the single terminal t8)

Hence the possible first–token sources are  
NT5, NT19, NT18, NT27, NT26, NT0, NT21, NT13, NT17, NT9, or the literal t8.

Now check which terminals these non‑terminals can produce directly:

NT5 → t8  
NT19 → t21  
NT18 → t23  
NT27 → t19 | t10  
NT21 → t0  
NT17 → t9 | t4  

NT26, NT0, NT13, NT9 have no direct terminal productions at all.

None of these options yield the terminal t28, which is the first symbol of the target string.

Therefore NT5 can never start a derived string with t28, and since S always puts NT5 first, the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

In this grammar the start symbol is fixed:

S → NT5 NT8

So any string generated by the grammar must be the concatenation of

 • a substring produced by NT5, followed immediately by  
 • a substring produced by NT8.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, NT8 can only expand through one of the three binary rules shown below:

NT8 → NT15 NT11  
NT8 → NT12 NT2  
NT8 → NT4 NT3

Hence the right‑most child of NT8 is always NT11, NT2 or NT3.  
Whatever string NT8 generates, its final (right‑most) terminal symbol therefore has to be produced by one of those three non‑terminals.

Terminals producible by those three symbols are:

NT11 ⇒ t6 | t1 | t28  
NT2  ⇒ t9  
NT3  ⇒ t12

Consequently, any string derived from NT8 must end in one of

 t6, t1, t28, t9, t12.

The string we are asked to recognise ends with the terminal t8 (the last two symbols are “… t8 t8”).  
Since t8 is not among the possible final symbols listed above, no derivation of NT8 can produce a suffix that ends in t8, and therefore no derivation of S (= NT5 NT8) can yield the given string.

Hence the supplied string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT5 NT8

Consequently the final part of every sentence produced by the grammar must be generated by NT8.

The only productions for NT8 are  

NT8 → NT15 NT11  
NT8 → NT12 NT2  
NT8 → NT4  NT3

All three are binary (the grammar is in CNF) and none of the non‑terminals on the right‑hand side is allowed to vanish (there is no ε‑production anywhere in the grammar).  
Therefore every string produced by NT8 must contain at least two terminals – one issued by the first right‑hand symbol and one by the second.

Look at the last terminal of the string we have to test: it is t1.  
Which non‑terminal can yield t1?

The grammar contains exactly one lexical rule that produces t1:

NT11 → 't1'

Thus the last symbol of any sentence ending with t1 would have to come from NT11.

Among the three rules for NT8, NT11 appears only in the first one:

NT8 → NT15 NT11

Hence, if a sentence ends with t1, that t1 must be preceded by whatever NT15 generates.  
But NT15 itself is defined only by

NT15 → NT11 NT9            (no lexical alternatives)

Consequently NT15 produces at least two terminals: the first from NT11 (t6, t1, or t28) and at least one more from NT9 (NT9 has no ε‑rule).

So NT8 can supply at minimum three terminals when it ends with t1:

first ≥1 terminal(s) from NT15, followed by the final t1 from NT11.

In the string to be tested the suffix consisting of the last three terminals is

… t18  t28  t1
        ↑    ↑
      (second‑to‑last) (last)

Because the second‑to‑last terminal is t28, NT15 would have to produce exactly “t18 t28”, with its own first terminal being t18.  
That is impossible: the first terminal produced by NT15 comes from its left‑hand NT11 and can only be t6, t1 or t28 – never t18.

Therefore NT8 cannot generate a suffix ending in “… t18 t28 t1”, and since NT8 is obligated to generate the final part of every sentence derived from S, the given string cannot be derived from the grammar at all.

Answer: No

The start symbol S rewrites once as

S → NT5  NT8

so the string must be the concatenation of two blocks,
a prefix generated by NT5 and a suffix generated by NT8.

NT8 has only three alternatives (all binary):
  NT8 → NT12 NT2        (the first terminal it produces is t28, t18, or t11)
  NT8 → NT4  NT3        (the first terminal it produces is t27)
  NT8 → NT15 NT11       (the first terminal it produces is t6, t1, or t28)

Hence the first token in the NT8‑part of any sentence must be one of
{t28, t18, t11, t27, t6, t1}.

Looking along the 30‑token string, the only places where such a token
occurs are just before positions

2, 3, 7, 8, 9, 10, 13, 16, 17, 19, 22, 26.

That means NT8 would have to cover one of the following suffixes:

(1)  t1 … t19   (29 tokens)        (too long: NT8 can’t start with t1 and
                                      generates at least two tokens)
(2)  t1 … t19   (28 tokens)        (same problem)
(3)  t18 … t19  (24 tokens)        (NT8 can’t start with t18 and produce
                                      t18 t1 as its first two tokens)
(4)  t1 … t19   (23 tokens)        (same problem)
(5)  t27 … t19  (22 tokens)        (NT8 → NT4 NT3 would force the second
                                      token to be generated by NT3, whose
                                      only 1‑token output is t12 – but the
                                      second token here is t27)
(6)  t27 … t19  (21 tokens)        (same difficulty)
(7)  t18 … t19  (18 tokens)        (as above)
(8)  t18 … t19  (15 tokens)        (as above)
(9)  t27 … t19  (14 tokens)        (as above)
(10) t28 t10 … t19 (12 tokens)     (NT8 could begin with t28 via NT8 → NT12
                                      NT2, but then NT2 would have to
                                      produce t10…t19.  The only way NT2
                                      expands (beside the terminal t9) is
                                      NT2 → NT4 NT27 or NT0 NT13; neither
                                      can yield a sequence beginning with
                                      t10.)
(11) t1 … t19   (9 tokens)         (NT8 can start with t1 only through
                                      NT8 → NT15 NT11, whose second token
                                      would be t6, t1 or t28 – not t9,
                                      the actual second token of the
                                      suffix.)
(12) t27 t21    (5 tokens)         (With NT8 → NT4 NT3 the second token
                                      must be generated by NT3; the only
                                      single‐token output of NT3 is t12,
                                      so NT27 t21 is impossible.)

All possibilities for the NT8 part therefore fail, so no split of the
form “NT5‑prefix  NT8‑suffix’’ exists.  Consequently the complete 30‑token
string cannot be derived from the start symbol.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT5 NT8  

so the string must split into a (contiguous) prefix generated by NT5 followed by a suffix generated by NT8.

1. Token ‘t8’ appears exactly once in the string (at position 29).  
   The only grammar rule that produces the terminal ‘t8’ is  
   NT5 → 't8'.  
   Therefore the unique ‘t8’ must lie inside the portion generated by NT5, i.e.  
   NT5 must cover the prefix ending at (at least) position 29.

2. The shortest derivations that NT8 can have all yield at least two terminals, because every rule for NT8 is binary:  
   NT8 → NT15 NT11 (≥3 tokens)  
   NT8 → NT12 NT2  (≥2 tokens)  
   NT8 → NT4  NT3  (≥2 tokens)

   Hence NT8 must be responsible for at least the last two tokens of the
   string.

3. The final two tokens of the string are

   position 30 : ‘t29’  
   position 31 : ‘t27’

   The set of non‑terminals that can generate each single token is
   • ‘t29’ → { NT7, NT16 }  
   • ‘t27’ → { NT29, NT4 }

   Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, any two‑token substring
   derivable by a single non‑terminal must come from a rule X → Y Z where Y
   generates the first token and Z the second.  Scanning every binary rule in
   the grammar shows that no rule has a left side X and a right side
   Y Z with Y ∈ {NT7, NT16} and Z ∈ {NT29, NT4}.  Consequently, no
   non‑terminal (and therefore certainly not NT8) can derive
   the two‑token string ‘t29 t27’.

4. Therefore NT8 cannot generate the required suffix, so the required split
   S → NT5 NT8 is impossible.  As a result, the whole string cannot be
   generated by the grammar.

Answer: No

The start symbol is  

S → NT5 NT8  

Hence any derived string w can be split as w = u v with  
u produced by NT5 and v produced by NT8.  
Because every production for NT8 is binary, the shortest string it can
generate is of length 2, so v contains at least two terminals.
Consequently the last two terminals of w belong to v.

In the questioned string the last two terminals are “… t23 t9”.
We must therefore ask whether NT8 can ever generate a string that ends
with the pair t23 t9.

NT8 has only three productions:

1. NT8 → NT15 NT11  
   The last terminal comes from NT11.  
   • NT11 → 't6' | 't1' | 't28' | NT29 NT9 | NT1 NT7  
     The only way for NT11 to end with t9 is through NT29 NT9, and that
     necessarily produces “… t27 t9”, not “… t23 t9”.  
   So this production cannot yield “… t23 t9”.

2. NT8 → NT12 NT2  
   Here the last terminal is given by NT2 → 't9'.  
   Therefore the preceding terminal must be the last one produced by
   NT12.  Inspecting every production of NT12

        NT12 → NT4 NT13 | NT17 NT10 | 't28' | 't18' | 't11'

   shows that none of them can end with t23:  
   • the single‑terminal alternatives give t28, t18 or t11;  
   • NT12 → NT4 NT13 ends with NT13, but NT13 can only finish with
     t27, t22, t29, t4 or t9;  
   • NT12 → NT17 NT10 ends with NT10, and every derivation of NT10 that
     ends in t23 actually ends with “… t23”, not “… t23 t9”.  
   Hence NT12 cannot provide the needed t23, so NT8 cannot end with
   “… t23 t9” via this rule.

3. NT8 → NT4 NT3  
   The last terminal comes from NT3.  
   NT3 can end in t9 only through the chain NT3 → NT12 NT17 with
   NT17 → 't9'. That makes the next‑to‑last terminal be the last one of
   NT12, and, as just seen, NT12 cannot end in t23.  
   All other ways for NT3 to end produce terminals different from t9.  
   Therefore this production also cannot yield “… t23 t9”.

Since none of the three possible first‑level derivations of NT8 can
produce a string whose final two terminals are t23 t9, NT8 can never
derive such a suffix. But the examined string necessarily requires NT8
to do so, because its last two symbols are exactly t23 t9.

Hence the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

Because the start symbol expands only in the form  

S → NT5 NT8  

the string must be divisible into a prefix generated by NT5 and a suffix generated by NT8.  
NT8 has exactly three productions in Chomsky normal form:

1. NT8 → NT15 NT11  
   (NT11 is the only non‑terminal in the whole grammar that can yield the terminal t6.)
2. NT8 → NT12 NT2  
3. NT8 → NT4 NT3  

Hence, if the string is in the language, its very last symbol must be explained by one of the two right‑hand non‑terminals appearing last in those productions:

• NT11 (from the first production),  
• NT2  (second), or  
• NT3  (third).

But

 • NT11 can yield only t6, t1, or t28;  
 • NT2  can yield only t9;  
 • NT3  can yield only t12.

The given string ends with the terminal t6, so the only viable production for NT8 is

 NT8 → NT15 NT11 with NT11 ⇒ t6.

Therefore the suffix generated by NT15 must be the sequence of the remaining four terminals preceding that t6:

 t8 t21 t27 t0

Yet NT15 has exactly one production:

 NT15 → NT11 NT9.

Consequently the first symbol produced by NT15 must come from NT11, but NT11 cannot yield t8 (it can yield only t6, t1, or t28). Hence no derivation is possible for the substring t8 t21 t27 t0 within NT15, and therefore no derivation is possible for the entire suffix within NT8. Because NT8 cannot generate the required tail of the string, the start symbol S cannot generate the whole string at all.

Thus the provided string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT5 NT8  

so the generated sentence is the concatenation of a string from NT5 followed by a string from NT8.  
Therefore the last token of any sentence in the language must be produced by NT8.

All productions having NT8 on the left‑hand side are

NT8 → NT15 NT11  
NT8 → NT12 NT2  
NT8 → NT4  NT3  

Every one of these is in Chomsky normal form, so the rightmost symbol in the derived string must come from the second non‑terminal on the right‑hand side:

• In NT8 → NT15 NT11 the last token is generated by NT11.  
  NT11 produces only the terminals t6, t1, or t28.

• In NT8 → NT12 NT2 the last token is generated by NT2.  
  NT2 produces only the terminal t9.

• In NT8 → NT4 NT3 the last token is generated by NT3.  
  NT3 produces only the terminal t12.

Hence the only possible final tokens of a sentence generated by NT8 (and therefore by S) are  

t6, t1, t28, t9, or t12.

The string we are asked to check ends with the token t21, which is not among these possibilities.  
Consequently the given string cannot be generated by NT8 and therefore cannot be generated by S.

No

Because the start symbol is

S → NT5 NT8,

the last two terminals of any string in the language must be produced by NT8.  
NT8 has exactly three binary productions:

1. NT8 → NT12 NT2   
   – NT2 can end only in the single terminal t9, or in the pair t27 t19 / t27 t10  
     (it is NT2 → NT4 NT27, NT4 → 't27', NT27 → 't19' | 't10').  
   – Hence every string derived through this rule ends with …t27 t19, …t27 t10 or …t9.

2. NT8 → NT15 NT11  
   – NT11 can be only t6, t1 or t28.  
   – So any string produced through this rule ends with one of those three terminals.

3. NT8 → NT4 NT3  
   – NT4 is the terminal t27, and every string produced by NT3 ends with t12.  
   – Therefore strings obtained here end with …t27 t12.

Consequently, for every derivation of NT8 the last two terminals must be one of
   t27 t19, t27 t10, t27 t12, or they must end in the single terminal t9 / t6 / t1 / t28.

The given string finishes with the pair

… t22 t19

which is not among those possibilities.  
Since NT8 cannot generate the suffix “t22 t19”, the start symbol S cannot derive the whole string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  

S → NT5 NT8  

so every derivation must split the string into two consecutive blocks: the first block produced by NT5, the second block produced by NT8 (in that order).

Look at every possible way NT8 can ultimately yield terminals.  The only direct productions for NT8 are  

NT8 → NT15 NT11  
NT8 → NT12 NT2  
NT8 → NT4 NT3  

Hence the last terminal of any string generated by NT8 must come from the second non‑terminal on the right‑hand side of one of those three rules:

• NT11 can produce only t6, t1 or t28  
• NT2 can produce only t9  
• NT3 can produce only t12 (its sole terminal rule)

Therefore the final terminal symbol of any string derived from NT8 is restricted to the set { t6, t1, t28, t9, t12 }.

The given string ends with t3, which is not in that set.  Consequently no derivation of NT8 can produce a suffix that ends in t3, so no derivation of S can yield the entire string.

Thus the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only way for the start symbol S to produce a string is via  

S → NT5 NT8.

Therefore the first token of any generated string must be the first token produced by NT5.

Lexical possibilities for the first token that NT5 can emit come from the left‑most symbol of each of its right‑hand sides.  
Those possibilities are:

• t8 (from NT5 → 't8')  
• t21 (from NT5 → NT19 …, with NT19 → 't21')  
• t23, t0, t15 (from NT5 → NT18 …, with NT18’s lexical rules)  
• t19, t10 (from NT5 → NT27 …, with NT27’s lexical rules)  
• t4 (from several alternatives beginning with NT26, NT0, NT17, …)  
• t3 (from NT5 → NT0 …, with NT0 → NT24 … and NT24 → 't3')  
• t9 (from NT5 → NT17 …, with NT17 → 't9')

Thus the only way NT5 can start with t21 (the first symbol of the given string) is through

NT5 → NT19 NT26 and NT19 → 't21'.

In this derivation NT19 produces exactly one terminal, so the second token of the whole string must be the first token produced by NT26.

But NT26 can only begin with the terminal t4, because its only base production is

NT26 → NT20 NT7 with NT20 → 't4'.

Hence every string derived from NT5 that starts with t21 must have t4 as its second symbol.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with

t21 t19 …

whose second token is t19, not t4.  
Consequently no derivation for the string can originate from NT5, and therefore S cannot generate the string.

Answer: No

The grammar is extremely dense and highly recursive:  

• Every terminal appearing in the string is produced by at least one non‑terminal in the grammar (e.g. t9 by NT17/NT2, t27 by NT29/NT4, t22 by NT7, …, t8 uniquely by NT5).  

• From the start‑symbol we have  
  S → NT5 NT8  
  where both NT5 and NT8 are themselves able to expand indefinitely because each is connected—through several layers of binary productions—to non‑terminals that (i) generate every terminal symbol and (ii) can be concatenated arbitrarily thanks to rules such as  
     NT5 → NT5 NT9,  NT9 → NT6 NT12,  NT6 → NT28 NT5, …  
  and  
     NT8 → NT15 NT11,  NT15 → NT11 NT9,  NT11 → NT1 NT7, …  

• The unique token t8 occurring in the input (position 28) is generated by NT5 → 't8'.  
  Owing to the rule NT5 → NT5 NT9 the outer NT5 can place this inner NT5 wherever needed inside the first component of S, leaving the remaining tokens to be supplied by the accompanying NT9 and by the second component NT8.  Thus the placement of t8 in the 28‑th position is readily accommodated.

• The two consecutive t0’s (positions 29–30) are produced by NT21 → 't0'.  NT21 can be inserted easily, because both NT5 and NT8 contain productions that introduce NT21 (e.g. NT5 → NT9 NT21, NT8 → NT12 NT2 with NT2 → NT4 NT27 and NT27 → NT21 …).

• No positional or ordering restrictions are imposed by the grammar: every non‑terminal occurring on the right‑hand side of any rule is itself reachable from NT5 or NT8, and through the dense web of mutually‑recursive rules any sequence of the available terminals can be assembled.

Because every token of the 45‑symbol string is individually generatable and the grammar freely permits their concatenation via the recursive binary productions, there exists a derivation of the whole string from S.

Yes

To be derived the string must be split into two parts,
since the start‐rule is  

S → NT5 NT8  
(the first part is generated by NT5, the second – the suffix – by NT8).

1. The given string ends with the terminal symbol t8.

2. Inspect every way NT8 can be expanded (the grammar is in Chomsky
normal form, so each production for NT8 has exactly two non‑terminals on
the right side):

   NT8 → NT15 NT11  
   NT8 → NT12 NT2  
   NT8 → NT4   NT3  

   Hence the very last non‑terminal that finally produces the last
terminal of the whole NT8‑substring must be NT11, NT2, or NT3.

3. Check what these three non‑terminals can produce:

   • NT11 can only produce t6, t1 or t28.  
   • NT2  can only produce t9.  
   • NT3, either produces the single terminal t12, or ends with
     NT17, NT7, NT13 or NT12 – none of which can yield t8
     (the only terminal rule giving t8 is NT5 → 't8').  
   Consequently none of NT11, NT2, NT3 (nor anything they can end with)
   can yield the terminal t8.

4. Therefore any string derived from NT8 can never end with t8.

5. Because NT5 generates the prefix and NT8 generates the suffix, the
whole sentence produced from S would have to end with whatever NT8 ends
with – but the given sentence ends with t8, which NT8 cannot produce.

Hence the grammar cannot generate the supplied string.
